                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-09</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I got this book by a suggestion from a friend. It was great. It is a story of a boy that is washed upon the shore of wales with his mother, a mysteriously beartiful woman calling herself Branwen. The boy has lost his memory, this sounds kinda overated right, wrong. From here it gets intresting. Emyers, as Branwen calls him,doesn't fit in with the other boys. One boy in particular causes a lot of trouble for Emyers, this also sounds kina borrin. However things turn for the worst, Emyers begins to grow into his powers. Thats sounds cool, a kid with supernatural powers. However Emyers powers are weilded in hate and anger, causing his magic to go horribly wrong. He ends up being blinded and Branwen takes him to live with some nuns. This suits Branwen fine but it doesn't bode to well with Emyers. The two have a fight and Emyers discovers his second sight, allowing him to see. Soon he can see well enough to get around he decides to leave, vowing never to use his powers again. Branwen gives him the Galator, a really important artifact and sends him on his way. He gets on a tiny raft he made himself and heads out to sea. He lands on Fincarya, a place between the land a sky. There he meets a Merlyn, a type of hawk, and a girl who lives in Druma Woods. The pair find a lot of Trouble (it being from two sources: the bird, named Trouble, and the blight that is killing Fincarya. The trio of friends then go on a quest, eventually defeating Rhit Gawar (i think i spelled that right) the bad guy.
<br />The story has a lot of suprise endings inculding Merlin's (he calls himself that in honor of Trouble who dies) decision to use his powers again, finding that when weilded with love and compassion his abilites can be better used. But the story isn't over, the land still needs to be healed from the blight that kills the land. New secets await our young hero in The Seven Songs of Merlin.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">This is the BEST book I ever read</div>
